","nameMeanings":[{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Lucy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Lucey  .","French: habitational name from any of various places called Lucy, originally named with the Latin personal name <i>Lucius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Lucey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Maeve, Niall.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Luasaigh</b>, an altered form of <b>Mac Cluasaigh</b>, a Cork name meaning ‘son of <i>Cluasach</i>’, a byname originally denoting someone with large or otherwise noticeable ears (from <i>cluas</i> ‘ear’).","English: variant of   Luce   1."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":15,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret De Lucy was born in 1275, in Cockermouth, Cumberland, England. She had at least 5 sons and 1 daughter with Sir Hugh Lowther III. She died in 1304, in Lowther Castle, Westmorland, England, at the age of 29, and was buried in England."},"et":{"1275–1304":"1275–1304","1288–1367":"1288–1367","1307–1345":"1307–1345","1340–1373":"1340–1373","–Female":"Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1304":"1304","1345":"1345","1367":"1367","1288":"1288","1275":"1275","1373":"1373","1340":"1340","1371":"1371","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","Cumbria, England":"England","Cockermouth, Cumberland, England":"Cockermouth, Cumberland, England","Lowther Castle, Westmorland, England":"Lowther Castle, Westmorland, England"},"fi":{"1275–1304":"1275–1304","1288–1367":"1288–1367","1307–1345":"1307–1345","1340–1373":"1340–1373","–Female":"Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1304":"1304","1345":"1345","1367":"1367","1288":"1288","1275":"1275","1373":"1373","1340":"1340","1371":"1371","1307":"1307","1290":"1290","Cumb